</p>
<div class="admonition tip"><p class="admonition-title"><span class="fa fa-lightbulb-o"></span> Tip</p><p>Actually, the <code>require_once</code> was also changed to <code>require</code>, which guarantees that
the <code>$loader</code> is returned.</p>
</div><p>Why? Well, the <em>whole</em> point of <code>bootstrap.php.cache</code> is performance: by having a
bunch of classes in one file, it means that the autoloading mechanism has to work
less. But when you're debugging, it's not helpful to see errors coming from a deep
line in <code>bootstrap.php.cache</code>.</p>
<p>Instead, in the <code>dev</code> environment, only include the normal autoloader. In <code>app.php</code>
do the same thing. But since performance is totally rad to have in the <code>prod</code> environment,
add an <code>include_once</code> below that for <code>/../var/bootstrap.php.cache</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="3d0d60b75f">
    <div class="meta">
